{"title_page": "List of oldest buildings and structures in Metro Manila", "text_new": "{{short description|Wikipedia list article}}\nThis article lists '''the oldest buildings and structures\u00a0in [[Metro Manila]]''', the [[Philippines]] that were constructed before 1900. Majority of the oldest extant buildings in the capital region are religious buildings built during the [[History of the Philippines (1521\u20131898)|Spanish Colonial period]]. Several buildings in the list have been reconstructed a few times with only a fraction of their original structures remaining. The buildings are sorted according to the year they were first built as inscribed on their [[Historical markers of the Philippines|historical markers]] installed by the [[National Historical Commission of the Philippines]]. The list excludes ruined buildings, monuments and road structures.\n\n==16th century==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Building\n!\n! Location\n! First Built\n! Inscription\n|- \n| [[Fort San Antonio Abad]]\n| [[File:Fort of San Antonio Abad - view towards Metropolitan Museum.JPG|100px]]\n| [[Malate, Manila|Malate]]\n| 1584<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bsp.gov.ph/publications/media.asp?id=5082&yr=2019 |title=BSP Governor Diokno Unveils Marker for Historic Fort Abad |publisher=[[Bangko Sentral ng Pilipinas]] |date=26 July 2019 |accessdate=15 March 2020}}</ref>\n| The origin of this fort dates from 1584. It was [[British occupation of Manila|captured by the British]] in 1762 and rebuilt at the beginning of the nineteenth century, when it was called La Polvorista because it was used as [[gunpowder magazine|powder magazine]]. The first battalion of the [[1st Colorado Cavalry Regiment|First Colorado Regiment]], under the command of Lt. Col. McCoy, took possession of this fort and hoisted the American flag over it on August 13, 1898.\n|-\n| [[Fort Santiago]]\n| [[File:Fort-Santiago.jpg|100px]]\n| [[Intramuros]]\n| 1593<ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.mb.com.ph/2020/01/07/fort-santiago-to-extend-operating-hours-starting-monday/ |title=Fort Santiago to extend operating hours starting Monday |publisher=[[Manila Bulletin]] |author=Baron, G. |date=7 January 2020 |accessdate=15 March 2020}}</ref>\n| Built of Guadalupe volcanic tuff by Governor [[G\u00f3mez P\u00e9rez Dasmari\u00f1as]] 1590\u20131593 in place of the wooden palisade of [[Raja Matanda]].\n|}\n\n==17th century==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Building\n!\n! Location\n! First Built\n! Inscription\n|- \n| [[San Agustin Church (Manila)|San Agustin Church]]\n| [[File:San Agustin Church and its remaining standing bell tower (the on the left was destroyed by an earthquake) (17106345010).jpg|100px]]\n| [[Intramuros]]\n| 1607<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.philstar.com/2014/05/26/1327519/san-agustin-church-not-just-one-those-old-churches |title=San Agustin Church: Not just one of those old churches |publisher=[[The Philippine Star]] |author=Eric N. |date=26 May 2014 |accessdate=15 March 2020}}</ref>\n| Oldest stone church in the Philippines. Plans were approved in 1586. Construction started in 1587 and completed in 1607 under the supervision successively of [[Order of Saint Augustine|Augustinian]] Fathers Francisco de Bustos, Ildefonso P\u00e9rez, Diego de \u00c1vila and Brother Alfonso de Perea. Its architect was Juan Macias. It has withstood many earthquakes from 1645 up to the present and survived the British invasion in 1762, the [[Spanish\u2013American War]] in 1898 and the [[Japanese occupation of the Philippines|Japanese invasion]] in 1942. The church choir has 68 carved molave seats with narra inlaids, an artistic lectern and parchment cantorals of the 17th and 18th centuries. The church and its graves were profaned during the [[British occupation of Manila]] in 1762. The ashes of early Spanish conquistadores [[Miguel L\u00f3pez de Legazpi]], [[Juan de Salcedo]], [[Guido de Lavezaris]], and Blessed Pedro de Zu\u00f1iga and others now rest in the easternmost chapel of the transept. Terms for the American occupation of Manila were prepared in the vestry of the church in 1898. The first Philippine [[plenary council]] was held here in 1953. Chosen as a [[World Heritage Site]] by [[UNESCO]] in 1993.\n|-\n| [[San Pedro Macati Church]]\n| [[File:Sts. Peter and Paul Church.JPG|100px]]\n| [[Makati]]\n| 1620<ref>{{cite web|url=https://opinion.inquirer.net/94663/san-pedro-macati-jesuits |title=On \u2018San Pedro Macati\u2019 and the Jesuits |publisher=[[Philippine Daily Inquirer]] |author=Rosales, A.M. |date=9 May 2016 |accessdate=15 March 2020}}</ref>\n| The [[Franciscans]] were the first missionaries here in 1578. The [[Jesuits]] built this church in 1620. Adjoining were the novitiate for the Jesuits and a house of retreat. Both the church and novitiate were dedicated to San Pedro in memory of the Rev. Pedro de los Montes, builder of the church, and of Captain Pedro de Britto, [[Regidor]] of Manila, who donated the site called Buenavista in 1607 and endowed the novitiate.\n|-\n| [[Nuestra Se\u00f1ora de Gracia Church]]\n| [[File:02516jfChurch and Monastery of Guadalupe Makati Cityfvf 08.jpg|100px]]\n| [[Makati]]\n| 1629<ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.abs-cbn.com/lifestyle/05/24/13/slideshowdoes-makati-have-soul |title=IMAGES:Does Makati have a soul? |publisher=[[ABS-CBN News]] |author=Pangilinan, R.M. |date=24 May 2013 |accessdate=15 March 2020}}</ref>\n| The foundations of this church and monastery of the [[Order of Saint Augustine|Augustinian Order]] were laid in 1601 and construction work was finished in 1629. [[Nuestra Se\u00f1ora de Guadalupe]] was chosen titular patroness in 1603. After the Chinese uprising of 1639, this sanctuary served as a seat of devotion for the Chinese. The buildings withstood the earthquakes of 1645, 1658, 1754 and 1863. The masonry roof of the church collapsed in the [[1880 Luzon earthquakes|earthquakes of 1880]] and the structure was rebuilt in 1882 by Rev. Jos\u00e9 Corujedo, O.S.A. Site of an orphan asylum and trade school administered by the Augustinian Order for the benefit of the children of the victims of the cholera of 1882. Both church and monastery were gutted by fire in 1899 during the early [[Philippine\u2013American War|skirmishes between Americans and Filipinos]].\n|-\n| [[Jes\u00fas de la Pe\u00f1a Chapel]] \n| [[File:08719jfBarangay Jesus Dela Pe\u00f1a Chapel Andres Bonifacio Avenue Marikina Cityfvf 05.jpg|100px]]\n| [[Marikina]]\n| 1630<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.marikina.gov.ph/visitors/where-to-go/san-isidro-labrador-parish-jesus-dela-pena-chapel |title=San Isidro Labrador Parish (Jesus dela Pe\u00f1a Chapel) |publisher=City Government of Marikina |accessdate=17 March 2020}}</ref>\n| At the former site of a warehouse now occupied by this church, the first mass was held on April 16, 1630, with the permission of Father Pedro de Arce, [[Bishop of Manila]]. The mass was held by Jesuit missionaries who discovered the image of Christ on a cliff and worshiped throughout the town of Jesus de la Pe\u00f1a which is now a village of Marikina.\n|-\n| [[Para\u00f1aque Cathedral]]\n| [[File:Saint Andrew Cathedral, Paran\u00f1aque City 2.jpg|100px]]\n| [[Para\u00f1aque]]\n| 1638<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.filipinaslibrary.org.ph/biblio/10893/ |title=Para\u00f1aque Church |publisher=[[Filipinas Heritage Library]] |accessdate=15 March 2020}}</ref>\n| The first Catholic missionary of Para\u00f1aque was the Rev. Diego de Espinal, O.S.A., companion of [[Juan de Salcedo|Salcedo]] in the reconnaissance of [[Ambos Camarines|Camarines]]. The veneration for [[Nuestra Se\u00f1ora del Buen Suceso de Para\u00f1aque|Nuestra Se\u00f1ora del Buen Suceso]] at Para\u00f1aque dates from 1625. The church and the convent were built by the Rev. Dionisio Suarez, O.S.A., parish priest from 1638 to 1650. This church was administered by the eminent historian, the Rev. Joaqu\u00edn Mart\u00ednez de Zu\u00f1iga, O.S.A. from 1801 to 1806. Para\u00f1aque is the birthplace of the Filipino botanist, the Rev. Ignacio Mercado, O.S.A.\n|-\n| [[Our Lady of the Abandoned Parish Church (Marikina)|Marikina Church]]\n| [[File:Nuestra Se\u00f1ora de los Desamparados Church.jpg|100px]]\n| [[Marikina]]\n| 1690<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.marikina.gov.ph/visitors/where-to-go/our-lady-of-the-abandoned-parish |title=Our Lady of the Abandoned Parish |publisher=City Government of Marikina |accessdate=15 March 2020}}</ref>\n| First built of thatch and bamboo by the [[Augustinians|Augustinian]] priests in Chorillo (now Barangka), 1572. Moved to Jesus de la Pe\u00f1a when the visita was transferred under the supervision of the [[Jesuit]] priests, 1630. The first mass was inaugurated and held, April 16, 1630. It was again relocated to its present site, 1687. The stone church was completed and became a parish, 1690. A large portion of the church was burned down during the [[Philippine Revolution]] and the [[Philippine\u2013American War]]. Its belfry was damaged during [[World War II]]. The church was renovated in 1951 by the parish priest with the help of citizens, religious and civic organizations.\n|-\n| [[Santuario de San Pedro Bautista]]\n| [[File:SantuariodeSanPedroBautistajf9800 11.JPG|100px]]\n| [[Quezon City]]\n| 1699<ref>{{cite web|url=https://lifestyle.inquirer.net/282306/cebturies-old-retablo-san-pedro-bautista-church-quezon-city-given-midas-touch/ |title=Centuries-old \u2018retablo\u2019 of San Pedro Bautista church in Quezon City given \u2018Midas touch\u2019 |publisher=[[Philippine Daily Inquirer]] |author=Sembrano, E.A.M. |date=18 December 2017 |accessdate=15 March 2020}}</ref>\n| The site was donated to the [[Franciscans]] on February 17, 1590 by Governor [[Santiago de Vera]] in the name of [[Philip II of Spain|King Philip II]]. Chapels were built of thatch and bamboo in 1590, of wood in 1593, and of volcanic tuff in 1599. The last was badly damaged in the Chinese uprising of 1639. Present church built from 1696 to 1699, through the generosity of Tom\u00e1s de Endaya. To this site retired for prayer and recollection several Franciscans who suffered martyrdom in [[Japan]] in the XVII century and others who led missionary expeditions to Japan, [[China]] and [[Cambodia]]. The escuela serafica or probation school for Filipino applicants to the Franciscan order was opened here July 16, 1931.\n|}\n\n==18th century==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Building\n!\n! Location\n! First Built\n! Inscription\n|- \n| [[Santa Ana Church]]\n| [[File:0680jfSanta Ana Church Main Right Facade Statue Exterior Patio Manilafvf 01.jpg|100px]]\n| [[Santa Ana, Manila|Santa Ana]]\n| 1725<ref>{{cite web|url=https://lifestyle.inquirer.net/100011/santa-ana-in-manila-fosters-community-based-heritage-tourism/ |title=Santa Ana in Manila fosters community-based heritage tourism |publisher=[[Philippine Daily Inquirer]] |author=Villalon, A.F. |date=22 April 2013 |accessdate=15 March 2020}}</ref>\n| First [[Franciscan]] mission established outside Manila in 1578. Present church built under the supervision of Vicente Ingles, O.F.M. Cornerstone laid on September 12, 1720 by [[Francisco de la Cuesta]], Archbishop of Manila and acting Governor of the Philippines. \n|-\n| [[Pasig Cathedral]]\n| [[File:03314jfSan Jose San Nicolas Sumilang Cathedral Museum Pasig Cityfvf 18.jpg|100px]]\n| [[Pasig]]\n|1760<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pasigcity.gov.ph/historical-spots |title=Historical & Tourist Spots |publisher=City Government of Pasig |accessdate=15 March 2020}}</ref>\n| The first Catholic Missionary of Pasig was Rev. Alonso de Alvarado, companion of [[Ruy L\u00f3pez de Villalobos]] in his expedition in the [[Moluccas]]. The first church was built in 1575. The present one was used by the British for military purposes in their campaign against the military forces of [[Sim\u00f3n de Anda y Salazar]].\u00a0\n|-\n| [[Santuario del Santo Cristo]]\n| [[File:San Juan, Metro Manila (2344411253).jpg|100px]]\n| [[San Juan, Metro Manila|San Juan]]\n| 1774<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sanjuancity.gov.ph/?page_id=13145 |title=Church of San Juan del Monte |publisher=City Government of San Juan |accessdate=15 March 2020}}</ref>\n| The church and convent were built in 1602\u20131604 by the [[Confraternity of the Holy Rosary|Dominican Province of the Most Holy Rosary]] on a site donated by Capitan Julian de Cuenca. Both buildings were burned during the Chinese uprising of 1639. The new church and convent, constructed in 1641, were set on fire in July 1763 during the [[British occupation of Manila]]. The present church and convent, constructed in 1774, were used by the insurgent forces of the [[Philippine Revolution]] of 1898. This sanctuary is the seat of the Confraternity of Sant\u00edsimo Cristo de San Juan del Monte approved by [[Pope Innocent X]] on March 4, 1648.\n|- \n| [[San Lazaro Hospital, Manila|San Lazaro Hospital]]\n| [[File:0066jfRizal Avenue DOH San Lazaro Hospital Shrine Santa Cruz Manilafvf 07.jpg|100px]]\n| [[Santa Cruz, Manila|Santa Cruz]]\n| 1784<ref>{{cite web|url=http://slh.doh.gov.ph/11-featured/2-san-lazaro-hospital-today |title=San Lazaro Hospital Today |publisher=[[Department of Health (Philippines)]] |accessdate=15 March 2020}}</ref>\n| Founded as dispensary in [[Intramuros]] by Fray Juan Clemente, 1577. Became hospital, 1578. Taken over by the Hermandad de la Misericordia, 1596. Transferred to new building at the premises of the [[Philippine Normal College]] becoming the San Lazaro Hospital, 1631. Turned over to the Hermanos de San Juan de Di\u00f3s, May 16, 1656. Building demolished for the protection of the city against the invasion of Chinese pirates, 1662. Transferred to another building nearby constructed by Fray Fernando de la Concepci\u00f3n, 1675. Moved to a building in the present compound, 1784. Enlarged, 1785. Further improved by Fray [[Felix Huerta|Felix de Huerta]] who built a chapel and enclosed the premises with stone wall, 1859. Taken over by the Americans, 1898. It became a contagious disease hospital.\n|}\n\n==19th century==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Building\n!\n! Location\n! First Built\n! Inscription\n|- \n| [[Las Pi\u00f1as Church]]\n| [[File:Saint Joseph Church, Las Pi\u00f1as.jpg|100px]]\n| [[Las Pi\u00f1as]]\n| 1819<ref>{{cite web|url=https://laspinascity.gov.ph/lifestyle/18/bamboo-organ |title=Bamboo Organ |publisher=City Government of Las Pi\u00f1as |accessdate=15 March 2020}}</ref>\n| Established as a [[pueblo]], 1762. Separated from the parish of [[Para\u00f1aque]], 1775. P. Diego Cera de la Virgen del Carmen apppointed first resident parish priest, December 26, 1795. The stone church was erected, 1797\u20131819. He created the [[bamboo organ]] from 902 bamboo tubes and 129 tin cans, 1816\u20131824. Slightly damaged by the earthquakes of 1828 and 1863. After the [[1880 Luzon earthquakes|1880 earthquakes]], the church was temporarily abandoned. It was renovated in 1883 but had not been fully repaired. It was used as a concentration camp during the [[Japanese occupation of the Philippines|Japanese occupation]] and as a hospital during the Liberation. Restored to its former use through a joint effort by the parish community and the Historical Conservation Society, 1962\u20131977.\n|-\n| [[Malate Church]]\n| [[File:Malate Church facade.jpg|100px]]\n| [[Malate, Manila|Malate]]\n| 1864<ref>{{cite web|url=https://lifestyle.inquirer.net/215301/restored-malate-church-is-the-one-the-community-remembers/ |title=Restored Malate Church is the one the community remembers |publisher=[[Philippine Daily Inquirer]] |author=Tejero, C.C. |date=7 December 2015 |accessdate=15 March 2020}}</ref>\n| This section of the city dates back to 1588. The titular patroness of this church is [[Nuestra Se\u00f1ora de los Remedios]], whose statue was brought from Spain in 1624 by Rev. Juan Guevara, O.S.A. The British landed their troops near these shores in 1762 and used the church of Malate for protection for their rear-guard in the [[British occupation of Manila|capture of Manila]]. This church was greatly damaged by the earthquake of June 3, 1863, and was rebuilt by Rev. Francisco Cuadrado, O.S.A. The parish has been under the successive administration of the [[Augustinians]], the secular clergy, the [[Redemptorists]], and the [[Columbans]].\n|-\n| [[Tondo Church]]\n| [[File:ChurchofTondojf1331 04.JPG|100px]]\n| [[Tondo, Manila|Tondo]]\n| 1880<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theurbanroamer.com/at-the-heart-of-tondo/ |title=At the heart of Tondo |publisher=The Urban Roamer |date=10 May 2018 |accessdate=15 March 2020}}</ref>\n| The first Catholic minister of Tondo was the Rev. Alonso de Alvarado, O.S.A. Tondo was the residence of [[Lakan-Dula]] who was baptized by the Rev. Martin de Rada, O.S.A. In the early days, its ecclesiastical jurisdiction extended up to [[Pasig]], [[Cainta]] and [[Taytay, Rizal|Taytay]]. Tondo was an active center of Catholic activities among the Chinese. The former convent was demolished in 1662 by Governor [[Sabiniano Manrique de Lara]] as a military precaution against the expected attack on Manila by Kue-Sing. The present church was built by the Rev. Manuel Diez, O.S.A. and the Rev. Casimiro Herrero, O.S.A. in the second half of the 19th century. Since the early days, the traditional fluvial procession of [[Santo Ni\u00f1o de Atocha|Santo Ni\u00f1o]] has attracted thousands of visitors to Tondo.\n|-\n| [[San Sebastian Church (Manila)|San Sebastian Church]]\n| [[File:SanSebastianChurch6234.JPG|100px]]\n| [[Quiapo, Manila|Quiapo]]\n| 1891<ref>{{cite web|url=https://newsinfo.inquirer.net/754191/an-eiffel-in-quiapo-saving-san-sebastian |title=An Eiffel in Quiapo: Saving San Sebastian |publisher=[[Philippine Daily Inquirer]] |author=Juego, A.T. |date=10 January 2016 |accessdate=15 March 2020}}</ref>\n| Designed by Genaro Palacios. The structural metal of which this church is uniquely built was manufactured in [[Belgium]] and erected here by Belgian engineers. The church was solemnly blessed August 16, 1891. Earlier churches built on this site by [[Recollect]] friars since 1611 were destroyed by earthquake in 1859, 1863 and 1880.\n|-\n| [[Tutuban station (PNR)|Tutuban station]]\n| [[File:Tutuban Center - main station, night (Tondo, Manila; 11-10-2019).jpg|100px]]\n| [[Tondo, Manila|Tondo]]\n| 1892<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pnr.gov.ph/getting-around/metro-commuter-line/24-history/126-pnr-historical-highlights |title=PNR Historical Highlights |publisher=[[Philippine National Railways]] |accessdate=18 March 2020}}</ref>\n| Preparation of general plan for railroad on Luzon authorized by royal decree, June 26, 1875. Royal approval of Don Eduardo L\u00f3pez Navarro's plan, May 11, 1883. Concession for the Manila\u2013[[Dagupan]] line awarded to Don Edmundo Sykes, January 21, 1887, and later transferred to the Manila Railroad Company Ltd. of [[London]]. Corner stone of the main station building at Tutuban laid July 31, 1887. Entire Manila\u2013Dagupan line, 195 kilometers long, completed and service inaugurated November 24, 1892.\n|-\n| [[Don Roman Santos Building]]\n| [[File:07351jfSanta Cruz Manila Buildings Lacson Streets Landmarksfvf 04.jpg|100px]]\n| [[Santa Cruz, Manila|Santa Cruz]]\n| 1894<ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.abs-cbn.com/ancx/culture/spotlight/08/04/19/from-wartime-shelters-to-dolphys-office-10-historical-landmarks-integral-to-manilas-identity |title=From wartime shelters to Dolphy\u2019s office: 10 historical landmarks integral to Manila\u2019s identity |publisher=[[ABS-CBN News]] |author=Reyes, I. |date=4 August 2019 |accessdate=15 March 2020}}</ref>\n| The building was occupied by Caja Ahorros y Monte de Piedad between 1894 and 1937. It was purchased and expanded by the Consolidated Investments Corporation and resold to the Magdalena Estate in 1944. Transformed into a hospital by [[American Red Cross]], 1945\u20131947 . Roman R. Santos purchased it in 1955 and was occupied by the [[Prudential Financial|Prudential Bank and Trust Company]] and trading offices. Its renovation was completed in 1957.\n|-\n| [[Pinaglabanan Church]]\n| [[File:Stjohnthebaptistchurchjf3035.JPG|100px]]\n| [[San Juan, Metro Manila|San Juan]]\n| 1896<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sanjuancity.gov.ph/?page_id=13147 |title=St. John the Baptist Church |publisher=City Government of San Juan |accessdate=17 March 2020}}</ref>\n| Designed and built by architect Luis Arellano in 1896 with the help of Mariano Artiaga and Mart\u00edn Ocampo. Destroyed during the revolution; Restored by Ram\u00f3n J. Fern\u00e1ndez after the [[Philippine-American war]] and became the parish of San Juan. The church was enlarged and renovated in 1951 under the leadership of parish priest, P. Hernando Antiporda. The improvement was made by architect Otilio A. Arellano who worked hard to maintain its original nave and fa\u00e7ade.\n|-\n| [[Taguig Church]]\n| [[File:Archdiocesan of St. Anne.JPG|100px]]\n| [[Taguig]]\n| 1896<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.taguig.gov.ph/tourism/taguig-landmarks/ |title=Taguig Landmarks |publisher=City Government of Taguig |accessdate=15 March 2020}}</ref>\n| [[Order of Saint Augustine|Augustine]] priests established the parish under the patronage of the patron saint of [[Saint Anne|Santa Ana]]. The first parish priest P. Diego \u00c1lvarez built and erected the first stone church in 1587. It was destroyed by the earthquake, 1645, and rebuilt by P. Andr\u00e9s D\u00edaz, 1848. It was damaged by another earthquake, 1882, and was rebuilt by P Guillermo D\u00edaz, 1886\u20131896. The church was renovated by Rt. Rev. Msgr. Augurio I. Jiuta, 1980\u20131985, and by Msgr. Emmanuel V. Sunga, 1985\u20131987. Presented to the Lord by the Honorable Bishop Bruno Torpigliani, [[Apostolic Nunciature to the Philippines|Apostolic Nuncio]] in the Philippines, in commemoration of the 400th anniversary of the parish, July 25, 1987.\n|}\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of Cultural Properties of the Philippines in Metro Manila]]\n* [[List of historical markers of the Philippines in Metro Manila]]\n* [[List of Roman Catholic churches in Metro Manila]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Metro Manila}}\n\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in Metro Manila|*]]\n[[Category:History of Metro Manila|Oldest buildings and structures]]\n[[Category:Lists of oldest buildings and structures|Metro Manila]]\n[[Category:Philippines history-related lists|Buildings and structures]]\n[[Category:Metro Manila-related lists|Buildings and structures]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Wikipedia list article}}\nThis article lists '''the oldest buildings and structures\u00a0in [[Metro Manila]]''', the [[Philippines]] that were constructed before 1900. Majority of the oldest extant buildings in the capital region are religious buildings built during the [[History of the Philippines (1521\u20131898)|Spanish Colonial period]]. Several buildings in the list have been reconstructed a few times with only a fraction of their original structures remaining. The buildings are sorted according to the year they were first built as inscribed on their [[Historical markers of the Philippines|historical markers]] installed by the [[National Historical Commission of the Philippines]]. The list excludes ruined buildings, monuments and road structures.\n\n==16th century==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Building\n!\n! Location\n! First Built\n! Inscription\n|- \n| [[Fort San Antonio Abad]]\n| [[File:Fort of San Antonio Abad - view towards Metropolitan Museum.JPG|100px]]\n| [[Malate, Manila|Malate]]\n| 1584<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bsp.gov.ph/publications/media.asp?id=5082&yr=2019 |title=BSP Governor Diokno Unveils Marker for Historic Fort Abad |publisher=[[Bangko Sentral ng Pilipinas]] |date=26 July 2019 |accessdate=15 March 2020}}</ref>\n| The origin of this fort dates from 1584. It was [[British occupation of Manila|captured by the British]] in 1762 and rebuilt at the beginning of the nineteenth century, when it was called La Polvorista because it was used as [[gunpowder magazine|powder magazine]]. The first battalion of the [[1st Colorado Cavalry Regiment|First Colorado Regiment]], under the command of Lt. Col. McCoy, took possession of this fort and hoisted the American flag over it on August 13, 1898.\n|-\n| [[Fort Santiago]]\n| [[File:Fort-Santiago.jpg|100px]]\n| [[Intramuros]]\n| 1593<ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.mb.com.ph/2020/01/07/fort-santiago-to-extend-operating-hours-starting-monday/ |title=Fort Santiago to extend operating hours starting Monday |publisher=[[Manila Bulletin]] |author=Baron, G. |date=7 January 2020 |accessdate=15 March 2020}}</ref>\n| Built of Guadalupe volcanic tuff by Governor [[G\u00f3mez P\u00e9rez Dasmari\u00f1as]] 1590\u20131593 in place of the wooden palisade of [[Raja Matanda]].\n|}\n\n==17th century==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Building\n!\n! Location\n! First Built\n! Inscription\n|- \n| [[San Agustin Church (Manila)|San Agustin Church]]\n| [[File:San Agustin Church and its remaining standing bell tower (the on the left was destroyed by an earthquake) (17106345010).jpg|100px]]\n| [[Intramuros]]\n| 1607<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.philstar.com/2014/05/26/1327519/san-agustin-church-not-just-one-those-old-churches |title=San Agustin Church: Not just one of those old churches |publisher=[[The Philippine Star]] |author=Eric N. |date=26 May 2014 |accessdate=15 March 2020}}</ref>\n| Oldest stone church in the Philippines. Plans were approved in 1586. Construction started in 1587 and completed in 1607 under the supervision successively of [[Order of Saint Augustine|Augustinian]] Fathers Francisco de Bustos, Ildefonso P\u00e9rez, Diego de \u00c1vila and Brother Alfonso de Perea. Its architect was Juan Macias. It has withstood many earthquakes from 1645 up to the present and survived the British invasion in 1762, the [[Spanish\u2013American War]] in 1898 and the [[Japanese occupation of the Philippines|Japanese invasion]] in 1942. The church choir has 68 carved molave seats with narra inlaids, an artistic lectern and parchment cantorals of the 17th and 18th centuries. The church and its graves were profaned during the [[British occupation of Manila]] in 1762. The ashes of early Spanish conquistadores [[Miguel L\u00f3pez de Legazpi]], [[Juan de Salcedo]], [[Guido de Lavezaris]], and Blessed Pedro de Zu\u00f1iga and others now rest in the easternmost chapel of the transept. Terms for the American occupation of Manila were prepared in the vestry of the church in 1898. The first Philippine [[plenary council]] was held here in 1953. Chosen as a [[World Heritage Site]] by [[UNESCO]] in 1993.\n|-\n| [[San Pedro Macati Church]]\n| [[File:Sts. Peter and Paul Church.JPG|100px]]\n| [[Makati]]\n| 1620<ref>{{cite web|url=https://opinion.inquirer.net/94663/san-pedro-macati-jesuits |title=On \u2018San Pedro Macati\u2019 and the Jesuits |publisher=[[Philippine Daily Inquirer]] |author=Rosales, A.M. |date=9 May 2016 |accessdate=15 March 2020}}</ref>\n| The [[Franciscans]] were the first missionaries here in 1578. The [[Jesuits]] built this church in 1620. Adjoining were the novitiate for the Jesuits and a house of retreat. Both the church and novitiate were dedicated to San Pedro in memory of the Rev. Pedro de los Montes, builder of the church, and of Captain Pedro de Britto, [[Regidor]] of Manila, who donated the site called Buenavista in 1607 and endowed the novitiate.\n|-\n| [[Nuestra Se\u00f1ora de Gracia Church]]\n| [[File:02516jfChurch and Monastery of Guadalupe Makati Cityfvf 08.jpg|100px]]\n| [[Makati]]\n| 1629<ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.abs-cbn.com/lifestyle/05/24/13/slideshowdoes-makati-have-soul |title=IMAGES:Does Makati have a soul? |publisher=[[ABS-CBN News]] |author=Pangilinan, R.M. |date=24 May 2013 |accessdate=15 March 2020}}</ref>\n| The foundations of this church and monastery of the [[Order of Saint Augustine|Augustinian Order]] were laid in 1601 and construction work was finished in 1629. [[Nuestra Se\u00f1ora de Guadalupe]] was chosen titular patroness in 1603. After the Chinese uprising of 1639, this sanctuary served as a seat of devotion for the Chinese. The buildings withstood the earthquakes of 1645, 1658, 1754 and 1863. The masonry roof of the church collapsed in the [[1880 Luzon earthquakes|earthquakes of 1880]] and the structure was rebuilt in 1882 by Rev. Jos\u00e9 Corujedo, O.S.A. Site of an orphan asylum and trade school administered by the Augustinian Order for the benefit of the children of the victims of the cholera of 1882. Both church and monastery were gutted by fire in 1899 during the early [[Philippine\u2013American War|skirmishes between Americans and Filipinos]].\n|-\n| [[Jes\u00fas de la Pe\u00f1a Chapel]] \n| [[File:08719jfBarangay Jesus Dela Pe\u00f1a Chapel Andres Bonifacio Avenue Marikina Cityfvf 05.jpg|100px]]\n| [[Marikina]]\n| 1630<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.marikina.gov.ph/visitors/where-to-go/san-isidro-labrador-parish-jesus-dela-pena-chapel |title=San Isidro Labrador Parish (Jesus dela Pe\u00f1a Chapel) |publisher=City Government of Marikina |accessdate=17 March 2020}}</ref>\n| At the former site of a warehouse now occupied by this church, the first mass was held on April 16, 1630, with the permission of Father Pedro de Arce, [[Bishop of Manila]]. The mass was held by Jesuit missionaries who discovered the image of Christ on a cliff and worshiped throughout the town of Jesus de la Pe\u00f1a which is now a village of Marikina.\n|-\n| [[Para\u00f1aque Cathedral]]\n| [[File:Saint Andrew Cathedral, Paran\u00f1aque City 2.jpg|100px]]\n| [[Para\u00f1aque]]\n| 1638<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.filipinaslibrary.org.ph/biblio/10893/ |title=Para\u00f1aque Church |publisher=[[Filipinas Heritage Library]] |accessdate=15 March 2020}}</ref>\n| The first Catholic missionary of Para\u00f1aque was the Rev. Diego de Espinal, O.S.A., companion of [[Juan de Salcedo|Salcedo]] in the reconnaissance of [[Ambos Camarines|Camarines]]. The veneration for [[Nuestra Se\u00f1ora del Buen Suceso de Para\u00f1aque|Nuestra Se\u00f1ora del Buen Suceso]] at Para\u00f1aque dates from 1625. The church and the convent were built by the Rev. Dionisio Suarez, O.S.A., parish priest from 1638 to 1650. This church was administered by the eminent historian, the Rev. Joaqu\u00edn Mart\u00ednez de Zu\u00f1iga, O.S.A. from 1801 to 1806. Para\u00f1aque is the birthplace of the Filipino botanist, the Rev. Ignacio Mercado, O.S.A.\n|-\n| [[Our Lady of the Abandoned Parish Church (Marikina)|Marikina Church]]\n| [[File:Nuestra Se\u00f1ora de los Desamparados Church.jpg|100px]]\n| [[Marikina]]\n| 1690<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.marikina.gov.ph/visitors/where-to-go/our-lady-of-the-abandoned-parish |title=Our Lady of the Abandoned Parish |publisher=City Government of Marikina |accessdate=15 March 2020}}</ref>\n| First built of thatch and bamboo by the [[Augustinian]] priests in Chorillo (now Barangka), 1572. Moved to Jesus de la Pe\u00f1a when the visita was transferred under the supervision of the [[Jesuit]] priests, 1630. The first mass was inaugurated and held, April 16, 1630. It was again relocated to its present site, 1687. The stone church was completed and became a parish, 1690. A large portion of the church was burned down during the [[Philippine Revolution]] and the [[Philippine\u2013American War]]. Its belfry was damaged during [[World War II]]. The church was renovated in 1951 by the parish priest with the help of citizens, religious and civic organizations.\n|-\n| [[Santuario de San Pedro Bautista]]\n| [[File:SantuariodeSanPedroBautistajf9800 11.JPG|100px]]\n| [[Quezon City]]\n| 1699<ref>{{cite web|url=https://lifestyle.inquirer.net/282306/cebturies-old-retablo-san-pedro-bautista-church-quezon-city-given-midas-touch/ |title=Centuries-old \u2018retablo\u2019 of San Pedro Bautista church in Quezon City given \u2018Midas touch\u2019 |publisher=[[Philippine Daily Inquirer]] |author=Sembrano, E.A.M. |date=18 December 2017 |accessdate=15 March 2020}}</ref>\n| The site was donated to the [[Franciscans]] on February 17, 1590 by Governor [[Santiago de Vera]] in the name of [[Philip II of Spain|King Philip II]]. Chapels were built of thatch and bamboo in 1590, of wood in 1593, and of volcanic tuff in 1599. The last was badly damaged in the Chinese uprising of 1639. Present church built from 1696 to 1699, through the generosity of Tom\u00e1s de Endaya. To this site retired for prayer and recollection several Franciscans who suffered martyrdom in [[Japan]] in the XVII century and others who led missionary expeditions to Japan, [[China]] and [[Cambodia]]. The escuela serafica or probation school for Filipino applicants to the Franciscan order was opened here July 16, 1931.\n|}\n\n==18th century==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Building\n!\n! Location\n! First Built\n! Inscription\n|- \n| [[Santa Ana Church]]\n| [[File:0680jfSanta Ana Church Main Right Facade Statue Exterior Patio Manilafvf 01.jpg|100px]]\n| [[Santa Ana, Manila|Santa Ana]]\n| 1725<ref>{{cite web|url=https://lifestyle.inquirer.net/100011/santa-ana-in-manila-fosters-community-based-heritage-tourism/ |title=Santa Ana in Manila fosters community-based heritage tourism |publisher=[[Philippine Daily Inquirer]] |author=Villalon, A.F. |date=22 April 2013 |accessdate=15 March 2020}}</ref>\n| First [[Franciscan]] mission established outside Manila in 1578. Present church built under the supervision of Vicente Ingles, O.F.M. Cornerstone laid on September 12, 1720 by [[Francisco de la Cuesta]], Archbishop of Manila and acting Governor of the Philippines. \n|-\n| [[Pasig Cathedral]]\n| [[File:03314jfSan Jose San Nicolas Sumilang Cathedral Museum Pasig Cityfvf 18.jpg|100px]]\n| [[Pasig]]\n|1760<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pasigcity.gov.ph/historical-spots |title=Historical & Tourist Spots |publisher=City Government of Pasig |accessdate=15 March 2020}}</ref>\n| The first Catholic Missionary of Pasig was Rev. Alonso de Alvarado, companion of [[Ruy L\u00f3pez de Villalobos]] in his expedition in the [[Moluccas]]. The first church was built in 1575. The present one was used by the British for military purposes in their campaign against the military forces of [[Sim\u00f3n de Anda y Salazar]].\u00a0\n|-\n| [[Santuario del Santo Cristo]]\n| [[File:San Juan, Metro Manila (2344411253).jpg|100px]]\n| [[San Juan, Metro Manila|San Juan]]\n| 1774<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sanjuancity.gov.ph/?page_id=13145 |title=Church of San Juan del Monte |publisher=City Government of San Juan |accessdate=15 March 2020}}</ref>\n| The church and convent were built in 1602\u20131604 by the [[Confraternity of the Holy Rosary|Dominican Province of the Most Holy Rosary]] on a site donated by Capitan Julian de Cuenca. Both buildings were burned during the Chinese uprising of 1639. The new church and convent, constructed in 1641, were set on fire in July 1763 during the [[British occupation of Manila]]. The present church and convent, constructed in 1774, were used by the insurgent forces of the [[Philippine Revolution]] of 1898. This sanctuary is the seat of the Confraternity of Sant\u00edsimo Cristo de San Juan del Monte approved by [[Pope Innocent X]] on March 4, 1648.\n|- \n| [[San Lazaro Hospital, Manila|San Lazaro Hospital]]\n| [[File:0066jfRizal Avenue DOH San Lazaro Hospital Shrine Santa Cruz Manilafvf 07.jpg|100px]]\n| [[Santa Cruz, Manila|Santa Cruz]]\n| 1784<ref>{{cite web|url=http://slh.doh.gov.ph/11-featured/2-san-lazaro-hospital-today |title=San Lazaro Hospital Today |publisher=[[Department of Health (Philippines)]] |accessdate=15 March 2020}}</ref>\n| Founded as dispensary in [[Intramuros]] by Fray Juan Clemente, 1577. Became hospital, 1578. Taken over by the Hermandad de la Misericordia, 1596. Transferred to new building at the premises of the [[Philippine Normal College]] becoming the San Lazaro Hospital, 1631. Turned over to the Hermanos de San Juan de Di\u00f3s, May 16, 1656. Building demolished for the protection of the city against the invasion of Chinese pirates, 1662. Transferred to another building nearby constructed by Fray Fernando de la Concepci\u00f3n, 1675. Moved to a building in the present compound, 1784. Enlarged, 1785. Further improved by Fray [[Felix Huerta|Felix de Huerta]] who built a chapel and enclosed the premises with stone wall, 1859. Taken over by the Americans, 1898. It became a contagious disease hospital.\n|}\n\n==19th century==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Building\n!\n! Location\n! First Built\n! Inscription\n|- \n| [[Las Pi\u00f1as Church]]\n| [[File:Saint Joseph Church, Las Pi\u00f1as.jpg|100px]]\n| [[Las Pi\u00f1as]]\n| 1819<ref>{{cite web|url=https://laspinascity.gov.ph/lifestyle/18/bamboo-organ |title=Bamboo Organ |publisher=City Government of Las Pi\u00f1as |accessdate=15 March 2020}}</ref>\n| Established as a [[pueblo]], 1762. Separated from the parish of [[Para\u00f1aque]], 1775. P. Diego Cera de la Virgen del Carmen apppointed first resident parish priest, December 26, 1795. The stone church was erected, 1797\u20131819. He created the [[bamboo organ]] from 902 bamboo tubes and 129 tin cans, 1816\u20131824. Slightly damaged by the earthquakes of 1828 and 1863. After the [[1880 Luzon earthquakes|1880 earthquakes]], the church was temporarily abandoned. It was renovated in 1883 but had not been fully repaired. It was used as a concentration camp during the [[Japanese occupation of the Philippines|Japanese occupation]] and as a hospital during the Liberation. Restored to its former use through a joint effort by the parish community and the Historical Conservation Society, 1962\u20131977.\n|-\n| [[Malate Church]]\n| [[File:Malate Church facade.jpg|100px]]\n| [[Malate, Manila|Malate]]\n| 1864<ref>{{cite web|url=https://lifestyle.inquirer.net/215301/restored-malate-church-is-the-one-the-community-remembers/ |title=Restored Malate Church is the one the community remembers |publisher=[[Philippine Daily Inquirer]] |author=Tejero, C.C. |date=7 December 2015 |accessdate=15 March 2020}}</ref>\n| This section of the city dates back to 1588. The titular patroness of this church is [[Nuestra Se\u00f1ora de los Remedios]], whose statue was brought from Spain in 1624 by Rev. Juan Guevara, O.S.A. The British landed their troops near these shores in 1762 and used the church of Malate for protection for their rear-guard in the [[British occupation of Manila|capture of Manila]]. This church was greatly damaged by the earthquake of June 3, 1863, and was rebuilt by Rev. Francisco Cuadrado, O.S.A. The parish has been under the successive administration of the [[Augustinians]], the secular clergy, the [[Redemptorists]], and the [[Columbans]].\n|-\n| [[Tondo Church]]\n| [[File:ChurchofTondojf1331 04.JPG|100px]]\n| [[Tondo, Manila|Tondo]]\n| 1880<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theurbanroamer.com/at-the-heart-of-tondo/ |title=At the heart of Tondo |publisher=The Urban Roamer |date=10 May 2018 |accessdate=15 March 2020}}</ref>\n| The first Catholic minister of Tondo was the Rev. Alonso de Alvarado, O.S.A. Tondo was the residence of [[Lakan-Dula]] who was baptized by the Rev. Martin de Rada, O.S.A. In the early days, its ecclesiastical jurisdiction extended up to [[Pasig]], [[Cainta]] and [[Taytay, Rizal|Taytay]]. Tondo was an active center of Catholic activities among the Chinese. The former convent was demolished in 1662 by Governor [[Sabiniano Manrique de Lara]] as a military precaution against the expected attack on Manila by Kue-Sing. The present church was built by the Rev. Manuel Diez, O.S.A. and the Rev. Casimiro Herrero, O.S.A. in the second half of the 19th century. Since the early days, the traditional fluvial procession of [[Santo Ni\u00f1o de Atocha|Santo Ni\u00f1o]] has attracted thousands of visitors to Tondo.\n|-\n| [[San Sebastian Church (Manila)|San Sebastian Church]]\n| [[File:SanSebastianChurch6234.JPG|100px]]\n| [[Quiapo, Manila|Quiapo]]\n| 1891<ref>{{cite web|url=https://newsinfo.inquirer.net/754191/an-eiffel-in-quiapo-saving-san-sebastian |title=An Eiffel in Quiapo: Saving San Sebastian |publisher=[[Philippine Daily Inquirer]] |author=Juego, A.T. |date=10 January 2016 |accessdate=15 March 2020}}</ref>\n| Designed by Genaro Palacios. The structural metal of which this church is uniquely built was manufactured in [[Belgium]] and erected here by Belgian engineers. The church was solemnly blessed August 16, 1891. Earlier churches built on this site by [[Recollect]] friars since 1611 were destroyed by earthquake in 1859, 1863 and 1880.\n|-\n| [[Tutuban station (PNR)|Tutuban station]]\n| [[File:Tutuban Center - main station, night (Tondo, Manila; 11-10-2019).jpg|100px]]\n| [[Tondo, Manila|Tondo]]\n| 1892<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pnr.gov.ph/getting-around/metro-commuter-line/24-history/126-pnr-historical-highlights |title=PNR Historical Highlights |publisher=[[Philippine National Railways]] |accessdate=18 March 2020}}</ref>\n| Preparation of general plan for railroad on Luzon authorized by royal decree, June 26, 1875. Royal approval of Don Eduardo L\u00f3pez Navarro's plan, May 11, 1883. Concession for the Manila\u2013[[Dagupan]] line awarded to Don Edmundo Sykes, January 21, 1887, and later transferred to the Manila Railroad Company Ltd. of [[London]]. Corner stone of the main station building at Tutuban laid July 31, 1887. Entire Manila\u2013Dagupan line, 195 kilometers long, completed and service inaugurated November 24, 1892.\n|-\n| [[Don Roman Santos Building]]\n| [[File:07351jfSanta Cruz Manila Buildings Lacson Streets Landmarksfvf 04.jpg|100px]]\n| [[Santa Cruz, Manila|Santa Cruz]]\n| 1894<ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.abs-cbn.com/ancx/culture/spotlight/08/04/19/from-wartime-shelters-to-dolphys-office-10-historical-landmarks-integral-to-manilas-identity |title=From wartime shelters to Dolphy\u2019s office: 10 historical landmarks integral to Manila\u2019s identity |publisher=[[ABS-CBN News]] |author=Reyes, I. |date=4 August 2019 |accessdate=15 March 2020}}</ref>\n| The building was occupied by Caja Ahorros y Monte de Piedad between 1894 and 1937. It was purchased and expanded by the Consolidated Investments Corporation and resold to the Magdalena Estate in 1944. Transformed into a hospital by [[American Red Cross]], 1945\u20131947 . Roman R. Santos purchased it in 1955 and was occupied by the [[Prudential Financial|Prudential Bank and Trust Company]] and trading offices. Its renovation was completed in 1957.\n|-\n| [[Pinaglabanan Church]]\n| [[File:Stjohnthebaptistchurchjf3035.JPG|100px]]\n| [[San Juan, Metro Manila|San Juan]]\n| 1896<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sanjuancity.gov.ph/?page_id=13147 |title=St. John the Baptist Church |publisher=City Government of San Juan |accessdate=17 March 2020}}</ref>\n| Designed and built by architect Luis Arellano in 1896 with the help of Mariano Artiaga and Mart\u00edn Ocampo. Destroyed during the revolution; Restored by Ram\u00f3n J. Fern\u00e1ndez after the [[Philippine-American war]] and became the parish of San Juan. The church was enlarged and renovated in 1951 under the leadership of parish priest, P. Hernando Antiporda. The improvement was made by architect Otilio A. Arellano who worked hard to maintain its original nave and fa\u00e7ade.\n|-\n| [[Taguig Church]]\n| [[File:Archdiocesan of St. Anne.JPG|100px]]\n| [[Taguig]]\n| 1896<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.taguig.gov.ph/tourism/taguig-landmarks/ |title=Taguig Landmarks |publisher=City Government of Taguig |accessdate=15 March 2020}}</ref>\n| [[Order of Saint Augustine|Augustine]] priests established the parish under the patronage of the patron saint of [[Saint Anne|Santa Ana]]. The first parish priest P. Diego \u00c1lvarez built and erected the first stone church in 1587. It was destroyed by the earthquake, 1645, and rebuilt by P. Andr\u00e9s D\u00edaz, 1848. It was damaged by another earthquake, 1882, and was rebuilt by P Guillermo D\u00edaz, 1886\u20131896. The church was renovated by Rt. Rev. Msgr. Augurio I. Jiuta, 1980\u20131985, and by Msgr. Emmanuel V. Sunga, 1985\u20131987. Presented to the Lord by the Honorable Bishop Bruno Torpigliani, [[Apostolic Nunciature to the Philippines|Apostolic Nuncio]] in the Philippines, in commemoration of the 400th anniversary of the parish, July 25, 1987.\n|}\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of Cultural Properties of the Philippines in Metro Manila]]\n* [[List of historical markers of the Philippines in Metro Manila]]\n* [[List of Roman Catholic churches in Metro Manila]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Metro Manila}}\n\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in Metro Manila|*]]\n[[Category:History of Metro Manila|Oldest buildings and structures]]\n[[Category:Lists of oldest buildings and structures|Metro Manila]]\n[[Category:Philippines history-related lists|Buildings and structures]]\n[[Category:Metro Manila-related lists|Buildings and structures]]\n", "name_user": "BD2412", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200e17th century:Fixinglinks to disambiguation pages, replaced:Augustinian\u2192Augustinian", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_oldest_buildings_and_structures_in_Metro_Manila"}
